			<ns0:name>b...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/105821748722532785568/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">leaving things as zeros works iff the regions can pass validation.  currently other than the asm code needed for trampolines, the HLT op code, and a few things like that, the service runtime doesn't know about instruction encodings and leaves it to the validator.  in order to maintain as much separation as possible, if we want to leave pages zero, we should probably ask the validator at runtime whether that's safe -- or "compile in" this knowledge for each architecture somehow, but keeping the knowledge of the cpu architecture in the validator module.</ns0:content><ns0:updated>2010-09-14T23:51:01.000Z</ns0:updated><ns0:published>2010-09-14T23:51:01.000Z</ns0:published><ns2:updates /><ns0:title>Comment 14 by b...@google.com</ns0:title><ns0:link href="http://code.google.com/p/nativeclient/issues/detail?id=506#c14" rel="alternate" type="text/html" /><ns0:link href="https://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/506/comments/full/14" rel="self" type="application/atom+xml" /></ns0:entry>